The successful encapsulation of VP16 into the CS-g-β-CD can be confirmed by the results of FT-IR and XRD. As can be seen from Fig. 9A, the FT-IR spectrum of VP16 shows a strong peak at 1765 cm−1, which corresponds to CO stretching vibration [32]. The characteristic peak of VP16 can be still observed on the spectrum of VP16 encapsulated CS-g-β-CD, confirming successful incorporation of VP16 into the CS-g-β-CD. In addition, pure VP16 exhibits sharp peaks in the range of 10°–35° (Fig. 9B), implying a highly crystalline structure of VP16 [33]; however, these characteristic sharp peaks are not observed in the VP16 encapsulated CS-g-β-CD, indicating that VP16 encapsulated in the CS-g-β-CD is in amorphous or disordered-crystalline phase [33,34]. The encapsulation ratio of VP16 in the CS-g-β-CD is determined to be 73.6% according to Eq. (1) described in Section 2.3 and the predetermined standard curve of VP16 (Fig. 10
                        ), which is much higher than those in CS (9.45%) and β-CD (19.8%). The significantly enhanced encapsulation ratio of VP16 in the CS-g-β-CD can be ascribed to the 3D porous network structure of CS-g-β-CD, and the encapsulation of VP16 in the CS-g-β-CD is illustrated in Fig. 11
                        .
